defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
default1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCTC, the national cycling charity, was founded in 1878.  CTC has 70,000 
defaultmembers and supporters, provides a range of information and legal services to cyclists, organises cycling events, and represents the interests of cyclists and cycling on issues of public policy.
default&#xa0;
default2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCTC’s ‘
defaultSafety in numbers
default’
default campaign (
defaultwww.ctc.org..uk/campaign/safety-in-numbers
default) has shown that ‘more’ and ‘safer’ cycling can 
defaultand should
default go hand in hand, as well as calling for the actions needed to ensure that they do.  CTC’s ongoing 
default‘
defaultRoad Justice
default’
default 
defaultcampaign (
defaultwww.roadjustice.org.uk
default) is highlighting the inadequacies of the responses to bad driving from the police, 
defaultprosecutors and the courts, while calling for action to improve these.
default&#xa0;
default3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCTC played a key role 
defaultin shaping the Times newspaper’s 8-point ‘Cities fit for cycling’ manifesto
default, and the subsequent parliamentary ‘Get Britain Cycling’ inquiry and report
default, whose 18 recommendations we 
defaultstrongly 
defaultendorse.  
defaultCTC’s President, the broadcaster Jon Snow, gave evidenc
defaulte both at the Commons Transport Committee’s original inquiry on the Government’s road safety strategy
default, and the ‘Get Britain Cycling’ inquiry
default, emphasising the importance of ‘leadership’ in order to get Britain cycling.
default&#xa0;
default4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn response, the Prime Minister has
default now publicly stated his ambition to launch a “Cycling revolution”.  The Government is now drafting a Cycle Delivery Plan, aimed at fulfilling this ambition.  CTC is represented on the steering group providing high-level input to this Plan, and recently ho
defaultsted 3 days of discussions with Department for Transport (DfT) officials
default to discuss proposals.  We also have regular dialogue with officials from DfT and other departments or governmental bodies, including the Highways Agency.
default&#xa0;
defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;
default5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCycling is essenti
defaultally a safe activity, causing little risk either to cyclists themselves or to other road users.  Its health benefits far outweigh the risks involved, i.e. despite those risks, cycling significantly increases one
default’
defaults average life expectancy.  Moreover, there 
defaultis good evidence that cyclists gain from ‘safety in numbers’, with cycling typically becoming safer as cycle use increases.  In other words, more and safer cycling can, and should, go hand in hand.
default&#xa0;
default6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCycle safety is nonetheless a good deal worse in Britain 
defaultthan in many neighbouring continental 
defaultcountries.  Despite its health and other benefits, people in Britain are deterred from cycling (or from allowing our children to do so) by both the actual and perceived risks involved.
default&#xa0;
default7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo maximise the health, economic
default, environmental and other benefits of more and safer cycling, the focus of action nationally and locally needs to be on removing those actual and perceived risks: unsafe road and junction designs, traffic volumes and speeds, irresponsible driving (and a le
defaultgal system that fails to respond adequately to this), and lorries.
default&#xa0;
default8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCycle training also 
defaultplays
default an important role, not only in giving would-be cyclists of all ages
default 
defaultthe confidence and skills needed to cycle safely and legally, but also 
defaultin improving
default driving st
defaultandards
default 
defaultas part of the driver training process, particularly for drivers of lorries and other large vehicles.
