default10
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBy contrast, the health benefits of cycling are vast.  A person who cycles regularly (but not strenuously) in mid-adulthood 
defaulttypically enjoys a level of fitness equivalent to someone 10 years younger, and has a life expectancy two years above the average. 
default 
defaultIt has been estimated that, thanks to these extra life-years, 
defaultthe 
defaulthealth 
defaultbenefits of cycling 
defaultoutweigh the risks involved by around 20:1, a figure now endorsed by the UK Government.
default  
defaultA population-wide study in Copenhagen found that, compared with those who 
defaultcycled regularly to work, people who did not do so had a 39% higher mortality rate, regardless of whether or not they sometimes took part in other physical activities at other times.
