default14
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2011, 61% of people surveyed on their attitudes agreed or strongly agreed that 
default“it is too dangerous for me to cycle on the roads.”
default 
default 
defaultIf we are to successfully deliver both ‘more’ and ‘safer’ cycling, it is vital to tackle the sources of danger and fear which deter people from cycling, and not to exacerbate those fears with misguided ‘safety awareness’ campaigns which overstate the risks
default of cycling.  
defaultWe return to these sources of danger and fear, and ways to overcome them, in answer to Questions 2 and 3.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default15
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn its previous report on the Government’s Road Safety Strategy, the Commons Transport Committee rightly criticised the Strategy’s lack of any targets.  However simplistic casualty reduction targets can be even more problematic than having no targets at al
defaultl. These have in the past created a perverse incentive for road safety officers 
defaultnot
default to encourage cycling, for fear that more cycle use would undermine those targets.
default&#xa0;
default16
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCTC therefore supports the Government’s 
defaultadoption of 
defaultrate-
defaultbased indicators 
defaultto measure cycl
defaulte safety,
default e.
defaultg. measuring cycle
default casualties
default per million km rather t
defaulthan simply the number of cyclist
default casualties
default (
defaultalthough we would have preferred 
defaultrate-based targets)
default.  We now encourage the use of similar rate-based targets or indicators for local road safety 
defaultpolicies 
defaulttoo
default.
default&#xa0;
default17
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCTC nonetheless recognises that many councils, particularly shire counties, lack the cycle use 
defaultdata 
defaultneeded to measure the risk of cycling reliably.  Yet they could easily measure
default 
defaultpublic perceptions of the safety of cycling, either in 
defaultaddition to a ‘risk-based indicator, or as a
default substitute for it while developing their cycle use monitoring capacity.  Perception-based indicators focus attention on the need to overcome perceived as well as actual danger.  Reducing fear can be expected to 
defaultboost cycle use, leading in turn to improvements in
default 
defaultactual cycle safety, via the ‘safety in numbers’ effect.
