defaultQ2: What could central and local government do to improve cycling safety?default&#xa0;
default18
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIf we are to encourage more as well as safer cycling, the key sources of danger and fear to be tackled are: unsafe roads and 
defaultjunction designs, traffic volumes and speeds, irresponsible driving (and a legal system which fails to respond adequately), and lorries.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default19
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCycle planning contributes 
defaultto wider aims of reducing motor traffic and safer streets.  However
default,
default it also depends on wider measures to achieve those aims.
default&#xa0;
default20
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA report for DfT by University College London found that
default:
default 
default“The key relationship is 
defaultbetween car use and physical 
defaultactivity. In 
defaultorde
defaultr to increa
defaultse levels of physical activity, 
defaultit is necessary to reduce use of the car.”
default  Traffic reduction can be achieved on an area-wide basis (e.g. through various forms of road user or parking charges, or simply by reducing the availability of road or p
defaultarking space), or on a more localised basis through the technique of “filtered permeability” (i.e. allowing pedestrian, cycle
default and/or public transport access.
default&#xa0;
default21
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn terms of safety, a Transport Research Laboratory report found that the most important infrastr
defaultucture-related measure for improving cycle safety was to reduce motor traffic speeds, whether through lower speed limits, 
defaulthigh 
defaultquality street design or by safe junction design (e.g. use of traffic signals, tight corners, providing clear cycle priority)
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default22
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe aim should be to create comprehensive networks of routes for cycling, which are not only safe but also convenient, direct, coherent and attractiv
defaulte, for people of all ages, backgrounds and abilities.  These networks should encompass the whole of the road network, thereby providing access to the full range of destinations people wish to reach. However, they should be supplemented wherever possible wi
defaultth high-quality traffic-free routes, making cycling not only safer but more attractive and convenient than car travel.
default&#xa0;
default23
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBroadly speaking, good cycle routes will 
defaulttend to 
defaultfall into 3 categories:
default&#xa0;
default24
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPhotographs in the appendix illustrate
default a variety of techniques that can be used to create cycle-friendly streets with low traffi
defaultc volumes and speeds, or traffic-free routes.
default&#xa0;
default25
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCTC has strongly advocated the concept of “cycle-proofing”, i.e. ensuring that consistent high standards of cycle-friendly planning and design are incorporated into all highway and traffic schemes.  The same g
defaultoes also for new developments and even for planned road maintenance work.  New York City’s Department of Transport has shown how 
defaulthigh 
defaultquality cycle facilities can be introduced 
defaultvery
default cost-effectively, by installing them in conjunction with a planned resurfa
defaultcing of the carriageway.
default&#xa0;
default26
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Government and Highways Agency issue a variety of design guidance on cycle-friendly infrastructure and planning. 
default 
defaultTheir underlying principles are generally sound, but they are contradictory and woolly.  In practice, a lot of r
defaulteally awful designs are adopted, which is often entirely compliant with at least one of the available guidance documents.  Meanwhile engineers and planners, from local authorities and the Highways Agency alike, readily admit they have had little or no trai
defaultning in the principles of cycle-friendly planning and design.  This situation needs to be rectified, if cycle-friendly planning and design is to become the norm
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultRecommendations
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultFor more information
default, see CTC’s campaigns briefing on cycle-friendly planning and design:
default&#xa0;
default27
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Government will shortly publish a Green Paper on the 
defaulttraining and testing of young or novice drivers.  CTC fully supports the anticipated proposals to require drivers to have a minimum number of lessons, and to reach the age of 18, before they can obtain a full driving licence. We also support restrictions o
defaultn young drivers carrying young passengers at night, and for ‘graduated’ licensing, whereby novice drivers forfeit their licence after accumulating just 6 points (instead of 12) for a period after passing their test.
default&#xa0;
default28
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever CTC also believes the Green Pap
defaulter is a vital opportunity to incorporate cycle awareness, and indeed some actual cycle training, into the driver training and testing process – and not just for young and novice drivers either.  We believe the minimum of 25 
defaulthours of instruction should incl
defaultude at least 5 hours of cyclist awareness training, preferably consisting of actual cycle training.  This would not only raise drivers’ understanding of how to interact with cyclists, but also encourage them to view cycling as a serious alternative to driv
defaulting beyond the age when they acquire a licence.
default&#xa0;
default29
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe also believe actual cycle training should be a requirement for obtaining a bus or goods vehicle driving licence, and that cycle training should be a compulsory part of the drivers’ Certificate of Professi
defaultonal Competence (CPC) process.  A growing number of local authorities are requiring their fleet drivers (e.g. those driving refuse vehicles) to undertake cycle training, with drivers themselves reporting positively on the experience.
default&#xa0;
default30
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPublic cycle safety a
defaultwareness campaigns should focus on the importance of looking for cyclists at junctions, and leaving space for cyclists when overtaking.  Drivers need to know that cyclists are trained to avoid being too close to the kerb, or to parked cars, for their own s
defaultafety (e.g. so they do not have to swerve outwards to avoid potholes).
default&#xa0;
defaultRecommendations
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default31
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCTC supports responsible behaviour by all road users. We do not defend irresponsible cycling, any more than the AA or RAC defend irresponsible driving.  Moreover we strongly support increased resources for road traffic policing – see next secti
defaulton.
default&#xa0;
default32
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever it is important not to overstate the role of irresponsible cycling in serious or fatal collisions.  Police data suggest that, in collisions between a cyclist and a motor vehicle, the police are about 3 times more likely to attribute responsibi
defaultlity solely to the driver than to the cyclist.  A Transport for London analysis o
defaultf serious or fatal cyclists’ in
defaultjuries in London suggest that around 5% involve disobedience of junction controls by cyclists, whereas 15% involve disobedience by drivers.
default&#xa0;
default33
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCy
defaultcle training can nonetheless play a valuable role, not only in giving people the confidence and skills to cycle more often, but also in encouraging responsible attitudes and behaviour.  It can raise awareness particularly among younger cyclists of the inti
defaultmidation (as well as the actual risks) that they can pose to pedestrians who are frail or who suffer mobility or sensory impairments.  CTC fully recognises that they too want to be able to get around without fear (as well as without danger), 
defaultjust as cyclis
defaultts themselves do.
