default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs the table on p3
default shows, lorries have a relatively low 
defaultinvolvement 
defaultrate in cyclists’ injuries, but 
defaulta very high involvement rate in cyclists’ fatalities – 
defaulti.e.
default a collision with a lorry is disproportionately
default likely to prove lethal.  Lorries cover only 5% of vehicle mileage in Britain, yet they account for around 20% of cy
defaultclists’ fatalities (and around 
default15% of pedestrian fatalities), rising to over 50% of cyclist fatalities in London.  Their 
defaultinvolvement 
defaultrate in cycle fatalities is far higher than 
defaultthat of 
defaultbuses.  The difference is likely to be that lorry drivers sit high up and are surrounded by metal, whe
defaultreas bus drivers are much lower, and are able to see cyclists both in front and to the side of them thanks to a much larger area of window.  Most lorry-cyclist fatalities involve a left-turning lorry, with the cyclist generally being hit by the front (typi
defaultcally the front corner) of the lorry, rather than by the side.
